actually care about. This is extremely powerful, and it's also intriguing at the same time.

00:05:39.119 --> 00:05:44.000
So I can imagine you wonder, well, how does QueryChat actually work?

00:05:48.959 --> 00:05:52.640
QueryChat is more than just a chat window sitting on top of a dataset.

00:05:53.200 --> 00:06:00.559
With QueryChat, you never have to think about how to get to an answer. You don't have to think about

00:06:00.559 --> 00:06:07.760
what filters to apply or how to extract information from the filter data. No, you simply ask any

00:06:07.760 --> 00:06:13.440
question that comes to mind and QueryChat handles the rest. And yeah, yeah, yeah, I hear you. You

00:06:13.440 --> 00:06:19.679
could also ask all those questions in a typical LLM chat tool, but QueryChat is different. You

00:06:19.679 --> 00:06:26.239
are not relying on the LLM to invent answers or reason about the data internally. No, every single

00:06:26.239 --> 00:06:32.399
question is translated into SQL, and this SQL is executed on the actual dataset and returned

00:06:32.399 --> 00:06:40.799
exactly as the data dictates. And very important, the SQL is always shown. This means you can see

00:06:40.799 --> 00:06:49.679
precisely what is being run. So that's great. All right. Four benefits of QueryChat. One, reliability.

00:06:49.679 --> 00:06:56.320
The LLM does not analyze or transform the raw data itself. It only generates SQL text. QueryChat

00:06:56.320 --> 00:07:01.760
handles the execution of that SQL via tool calling, so all the results come from the real

00:07:01.760 --> 00:07:09.359
data engine and not from the model's internal guesswork. Two, transparency. Every query reveals

00:07:09.359 --> 00:07:15.359
the full SQL statement. Nothing is hidden, nothing is adjusted, and you always know how the answer was

00:07:15.359 --> 00:07:24.239
produced. Three, reproducibility. Since every SQL query is visible, analysis can be reused, shared,

00:07:24.239 --> 00:07:31.119
and audited. And four, safety. QueryChat's tools are designed with read-only actions in mind,

00:07:31.119 --> 00:07:35.760
meaning the LLM is essentially unable to perform any destructive actions.

00:07:37.359 --> 00:07:42.880
All right, let's go back for a second. I mentioned QueryChat handles execution of the SQL via

00:07:42.880 --> 00:07:48.559
something called tool calling. Well, tool calling is essentially a bridge between an LLM and your R

00:07:48.559 --> 00:07:55.920
session. The model does not execute code. Instead, it requests your R session to execute a certain

00:07:55.920 --> 00:08:02.559
function with certain inputs. Once R performs the execution, the result is then passed back

00:08:02.559 --> 00:08:09.839
to the model for interpretation. But the LLM does need to know something about your data,

00:08:09.839 --> 00:08:15.359
you know, things like which columns are there, what do they mean, and what type are they.

00:08:16.000 --> 00:08:22.880
This schema information is shared with the model, but not the raw data itself. With this information,

00:08:22.880 --> 00:08:28.640
it produces a SQL query as a tool call. Now, to run SQL, you do need a database engine,

00:08:28.640 --> 00:08:35.760
and QueryChat's weapon of choice is WDB. If you have your own database, that's no problem too.

00:08:35.760 --> 00:08:42.080
Whatever DBI, this is a database interface package for R, supports can be used by QueryChat.

00:08:42.559 --> 00:08:43.520
Pretty clever, huh?

